<font color="#FF0000">TO BARRY SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20  5:47:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Barry, I am not a Hawaiian historian, but let me answer what questions I can and lets move on.  First there is a sovereignty movement among the Hawaiian population who are seeking redress for acts committed against the Hawaiian people way back when.  The governor of the state, along with the state legislature and the President of the US and I believe, the Congress of the US, have admitted that these acts did occur and have issued the apologies for said acts. What is going on now is the Hawaiian groups trying to obtain a settlement and self determination status as the American Indian tribes have already done.  This has nothing to do with what we are discussing that I can see and for our purposes, is a moot point.<br><br>
As to the other points you are trying to make, I have already conceeded that Hawaii does, indeed, have their problems. I absolutely would never call Hawaii, or anyplace else, the &quot;ultimate melting pot&quot; as there is not always peace and harmony.  I, however, contend, that it is a hell of a lot closer to it than anywhere else that I have ever visited.<br><br>
&gt;When I wrote of multi-culturalism, it was more in thinking &gt;with the group-speak, the need for every group it seems (at &gt;least here on the mainland) to preference their being an &gt;American, i.e. Afro-American, Hispanic-American, etc.<br><br>
When I was in 'Nam with my unit, we had with us a Kit Carson scout who would not talk to anybody about anything even after much prompting. That was, until someone would mention &quot;the states&quot; and then no one could shut him up. He would talk about how he would come to the US, get himself a good education so he would become smart like all the other Americans, he would forget how to speak Vietnamese and get rid of his accent and talk just like the other Americans, he would get himself a good job so that he could be rich just like the other Americans. This is the only thing that he wanted to talk about, how to be an American.<br><br>
And I can just imagine how he was greeted upon landing at our shores. By your own admission, Barry, he would have run into a wall of anti-Vietnamese sentiment and hostility.  And you wonder why there are these enclaves?  Fact: If I am in the bush alone, I am going to die!  In order to survive the garbage thrush upon these people, they have to band together, make their own jobs, make their own community. These enclaves and the walls around them were built not by the occupants but by the prejudice and hostility of those around them.<br><br>
Personally, the only reason why anyone would consider the concept of cultural pride as absurd is because one is threaten by these other cultures. What, in Gods name, could there be any other reason? Why would anyone be threaten by the fact that the Vietnamese celebrate Tet, the Chinese celebrate a different New Year, that the Jews celebrate Hannakah(sp?). Why would anyone outside of that particular group, even care other than to be respectful. Why does the fact that there are more than a single language threaten anybody?<br><br>
You keep speaking about these groups thrusting or shoving their culture into your face. I don't understand the need to hide ones ethnic identity or cultural customs in ones house. How does the fact that a Hindu with a particular small shrine in the far recess of his very own shop, threaten a white, anglo saxon, protestant? Jeez, he is not the one going house to house every other day trying to get you to convert to his religion. How does the fact that the Japanese having a Bon Dance every year threaten your manhood?  How does the Chinese celebrating their calander New Year take money out of your pocket?<br><br>
Look, Barry, you can throw that &quot;political correctness&quot; term around all you want. Frankly, I believed it to have been coined by some fat farts in the radio and television industy who want to make money off of you and me and have them thinking for us instead of us thinking for ourselves. The same with the asshole republicans coining the word &quot;libral&quot; for their owns ends and the dumbfucks democrats doing likewise with the term &quot;conservative&quot;. What I do is lean on my own experiences, my own common sense, and what I feel is right and just. Your concept of Americanism never did exist and probably never will. We have always been an ethnically divided society. The only difference now is that people are not afraid to take pride in their heritage and their culture. And it seems that this pride is the threatening factor in this discussion.<br><br>
And, for the life of me, I just do not understand why.<br><br>

